<paragraph blockId="20.[151,1437,604,1026]" pageId="20" pageNumber="450">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,439,676,702]" pageId="20" pageNumber="450">Diagnostic features.</emphasis>
Living specimens have the dorsal surface light castaneous to orange-castaneous (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURES 53–55" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1065,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-284@20.[152,1436,1050,1958]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 53–55. Diceraeus melacanthus. 53: Dorsal view, scale bar = 1.0 mm. 54: Ventral view. 55: Distribution within Rio Grande do Sul." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692235/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="450">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
) and ventral surface green (
<figureCitation box="[504,591,712,739]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–55" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1065,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-284@20.[152,1436,1050,1958]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 53–55. Diceraeus melacanthus. 53: Dorsal view, scale bar = 1.0 mm. 54: Ventral view. 55: Distribution within Rio Grande do Sul." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692235/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="450">Fig. 54</figureCitation>
). Mandibular plates longer than clypeus, acute apically (
<figureCitation box="[1241,1327,712,739]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–55" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1065,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-284@20.[152,1436,1050,1958]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 53–55. Diceraeus melacanthus. 53: Dorsal view, scale bar = 1.0 mm. 54: Ventral view. 55: Distribution within Rio Grande do Sul." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692235/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="450">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
). Internal angles and posterior margin of cicatrices of pronotum dark castaneous. Anterolateral margins of pronotum concave and serrate, with pale outline (
<figureCitation box="[498,583,784,811]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–55" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1065,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-284@20.[152,1436,1050,1958]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 53–55. Diceraeus melacanthus. 53: Dorsal view, scale bar = 1.0 mm. 54: Ventral view. 55: Distribution within Rio Grande do Sul." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692235/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="450">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
). Humeral angles dark, strongly developed into an elongate spine, directed laterally (
<figureCitation box="[259,343,820,847]" captionStart="FIGURES 53–55" captionStartId="20.[151,264,1981,2005]" captionTargetBox="[162,1427,1065,1952]" captionTargetId="figure-284@20.[152,1436,1050,1958]" captionTargetPageId="20" captionText="FIGURES 53–55. Diceraeus melacanthus. 53: Dorsal view, scale bar = 1.0 mm. 54: Ventral view. 55: Distribution within Rio Grande do Sul." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4692235" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4692235/files/figure.png" pageId="20" pageNumber="450">Fig. 53</figureCitation>
). Pale spots along lateral margins of scutellum and corium, apex of scutellum pale. Connexivum green in live specimens and straw-colored in mounted specimens, with anterior angles maculate and posterior angle produced. Posterior margin of abdominal sternite 7 strongly acute. Body length: 10.00 mm.
</paragraph>
